The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Wednesday, March 31, 2004 				 IIT ties up with Canada varsity
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, March 30: The Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur today signed a memorandum of understanding with the University of Waterloo, Canada, for mutual cooperation in research, scholarship and exchange programmes.																								A team of IIT Kharagpur professors, led by P.P. Chakraborty, made a presenta- tion highlighting the stren- gths of the institute before a 20-member delegation from Canada.																								India is a science and technology giant and we want to establish ties between the best in India and the best in our country, said Ravi Seethapathy, the head of the delegation, comprising of representatives from leading universities and tech schools in Canada.																								Some of the universities are also signing up with IITs in Delhi and Chennai, he added.																								The association will be mutually beneficial, said an IIT professor.																								Chakraborty said the IIT will draw up a time-based action plan in the next six to eight months that will include, among others, partnerships in research projects and exchange of students and faculties.																								A. Chakma, vice-president, academic and provost, of the Canadian university, said the institute was looking forward to joint activities in areas like information, communication and technology.																								S.K. Dubey, the director of IIT Kharagpur, said: In the fast changing world of technology, tying-up with other universities is a must.																								At IIT, we believe that we should share knowledge with others and have had 20 such tie-ups in the last year. The tie-ups have yielded positive results for us.
